Operator Description <code>$eq</code> Equal to value <code>$ne</code> Not equal to value <code>$gt</code> Greater than value <code>$gte</code> Greater than or equal to value <code>$lt</code> Less than value <code>$lte</code> Less than or equal to value <p>For example:</p> <pre><code>{
    "user_id": {
        "$eq": 1
    }
}
</code></pre> <p>The <code>$eq</code> operator can be omitted, so the following query is equivalent to the above:</p> <pre><code>{
    "user_id": 1
}
</code></pre>

Operator Description <code>$in</code> In array (string, int, float) <code>$nin</code> Not in array (string, int, float) <p>For example: <pre><code>{
    "field_name": {
        "$in": [
            &lt;value1&gt;,
            &lt;value2&gt;,
            ...
        ]
    }
}
</code></pre></p>

PythonSQL <p>Use the <code>table.update()</code> method to update the specified records with filters.</p> <p>For example, update the record with <code>id</code> equals to 1.</p> <pre><code>table.update(
    values={
        "content": "TiDB Cloud Serverless is a fully-managed, auto-scaling cloud database service",
        "embedding": [0.1, 0.2, 0.4],
        "meta": {"category": "dbass"},
    },
    filters={
        "id": 1
    },
)
</code></pre> <p>Use the <code>UPDATE</code> statement to update the specified records with filters.</p> <pre><code>UPDATE items
SET
    content = 'TiDB Cloud Serverless is a fully-managed, auto-scaling cloud database service',
    embedding = '[0.1, 0.2, 0.4]',
    meta = '{"category": "dbass"}'
WHERE id = 1;
</code></pre>

PythonSQL <p>Use the <code>table.delete()</code> method to delete specified data records with filters.</p> <pre><code>table.delete(
    filters={
        "id": 2
    }
)
</code></pre> <p>Use the <code>DELETE</code> statement to delete the specified records with filters.</p> <pre><code>DELETE FROM items WHERE id = 2;
</code></pre>

PythonSQL <p>To clean all data in the table but keep the table structure, use the <code>table.truncate()</code> method.</p> <pre><code>table.truncate()
</code></pre> <p>Check the table is truncated, should be 0 rows.</p> <pre><code>table.rows()
</code></pre> <p>To clean all data in the table but keep the table structure, use the <code>TRUNCATE TABLE</code> statement.</p> <pre><code>TRUNCATE TABLE items;
</code></pre> <p>Check the table is truncated, should be 0 rows.</p> <pre><code>SELECT COUNT(*) FROM items;
</code></pre>

PythonSQL <p>To remove the specified table from the database permanently, use the <code>db.drop_table()</code> method.</p> <pre><code>db.drop_table("items")
</code></pre> <p>Check the table is removed from the database.</p> <pre><code>db.table_names()
</code></pre> <p>To remove the specified table from the database permanently, use the <code>DROP TABLE</code> statement.</p> <pre><code>DROP TABLE items;
</code></pre> <p>Check the table is removed from the database.</p> <pre><code>SHOW TABLES;
</code></pre>
